<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
(Figs 12, 13, 14D). Larvae mine the adaxial side of leaves of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. lessertiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="lessertiana">M. lessertiana</taxonomicName>
, forming a slender serpentine mine (Fig. 12A, B), and gradually expanding as they feed and grow forming a full-depth mine (Fig. 12G, L). Larvae consumed small amounts of leaf tissue (under 2 cm in leaf length) when feeding on seedlings (Fig. 13G, H). The young larva is about 1.5 mm long (Fig. 12I) and later instar larvae are 4-8 mm long (Fig. 12J, K). Larvae were collected from fresh leaves of seedlings. There was usually only one mine per leaf (Fig. 12A, B, G, H). The pupal cocoon is prepared outside the mine, on either surface of the leaf; the cocoon is greyish white to ochreous and near ellipsoidal in shape (Fig. 12M); 4.0-5.0 mm in length, 1.0-3.0 mm in width.
</paragraph>
